<%- include('../../partials/implementer-core.md.ejs', { specificsBlock: `## Java + Spring Boot Specifics

### Controllers and DI
- Annotate REST controllers with \`@RestController\` and \`@RequestMapping\`; keep them thin.
- Use constructor injection exclusively — never field injection with \`@Autowired\`.
- Validate request bodies with \`@Valid\` + Bean Validation annotations (\`@NotNull\`, \`@Size\`, etc.).
- Return \`ResponseEntity<T>\` with explicit HTTP status codes from controller methods.

### Service Layer
- Place all business logic in \`@Service\`-annotated classes; never in controllers or repositories.
- Use \`@Transactional\` at the service layer; never annotate repository methods directly.

### Testing
- Use \`@SpringBootTest\` + \`MockMvc\` for full integration tests of the HTTP layer.
- Use \`@DataJpaTest\` for repository-layer tests with an in-memory database.
- Use JUnit 5 (\`@Test\`, \`@ParameterizedTest\`) — never JUnit 4 (\`@RunWith\`).

### Anti-patterns to avoid
- Never use field injection (\`@Autowired private Foo foo;\`) — breaks testability.
- Never expose JPA entities directly as REST responses — map to DTOs.
- Never throw \`RuntimeException\` directly — define domain-specific exceptions.
- Never use \`Optional.get()\` without \`isPresent()\` check — use \`orElseThrow\`.
- Never put business logic in \`@Entity\` classes.` }) %>
